<br>
As stated, Memory and Bus speed for your internal motherboard are good to get up there. For example, they have 100MHz SDRam and 133MHz SDRam. They also have something called DDR ram, which would add whole levels of improvement over SDRam, but tends to be much more expensive. More memory = less paging things out to disk = faster loading/less lag in high memory areas (large zones with lots of graphics, high detail, etc)<br>
<br>
Video Chips themselves are good to move up in scale. GeForce 2's are ok these days, depending on the support the chip has on the Video Card (ie: GeForce 2MX is gonna bite, but a GeForce 2Ti is going to do much better). Also, AGP Port speed (4x better than 1x) and memory on board the video card play a large part. Again, like with system memory, more and better video memory means less having to go from video to system memory for textures, the video card can handle everything internal, and not bog down your system with transfering graphic data repeatedly. Video cards are going to cause lots of lag using new models (when they're in front of you), particle effects, laggy when 'looking' at something of high detail.<br>
<br>
CPU speed is enh, but certainly doesn't hurt to have a good processor. Nowadays, CPU speed tends not to be the bottleneck in your system, capable of far more processing power than it can get in data.<br>
<br>
Internet connections, faster is better, but after a certain mark, added speed does no good. Everquest was originally designed to be run over dialup, and while dialup tends to have flaws in it that cause slowness and latency, even the first step of Cable Modems is far more bandwidth than EQ will use. Reliable data transport (clean lines) and low latency through your ISP (watch your pings in game to see if it's good or not, should be 100-300 for good transport) are the more important things than bandwidth or comparisons between various high speed options.<br>
<br>
Making sure one of these is not substandard or slowing your PC unnecessarily is key. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://&quot;http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886&quot;"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ninjacorp.com/Rhasin_sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kannt00>Kannt00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#333333>(1/24/03 12:00:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8555.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: um</span><hr size=1> oh yes, rhasin's post reminded me -- to use the Radeon 9700 pro or the Nvidia FX, I believe your motherboard will need to support AGP 8x to take full advantage of the cards.<br>
<br>
